<h3>How It Works</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>App declares intent</strong> — The application provides a <code>LoaderIntent</code> object via the injector system (<code>customContexts:loaderIntent</code>). This declares the preferred loading UX: strategy, scope, progress, context, and timing.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumer resolves intent</strong> — A loading consumer (e.g., <code>&lt;route-view&gt;</code>) walks the injector chain to find the declared intent.</li>
    <li><strong>Traits selected</strong> — Based on the intent's dimension values, the consumer composes the matching Resource Loader traits (e.g., <code>withSoftBlocking</code> + <code>withIndeterminate</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>Traits apply behavior</strong> — During the async operation, selected traits apply DOM, ARIA, and CSS changes. On resolve, traits clean up and the consumer stamps its content normally.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Provisioning Chain</h3>
<pre><code class="language-text">App declares LoaderIntent profile
  → Injector provides customContexts:loaderIntent
    → Consumer resolves intent from ancestor injector
      → Consumer selects matching Resource Loader trait(s)
        → Trait applies DOM/CSS/ARIA changes during async operation
          → On resolve: trait cleans up, consumer renders result</code></pre>

<h4>Full Setup Example (with Router)</h4>
<pre><code class="language-javascript">// 1. App declares its loader intent profile
const docInjector = injectors.getInjectorOf(document);

docInjector.set('customContexts:loaderIntent', {
  strategy: 'soft',           // keep content visible, disable interaction
  scope: 'region',            // route-view is the loading region
  progress: 'indeterminate',  // no measurable progress for route loads
  context: 'transition',      // routes always have prior content (except initial)
  timing: 'debounced'         // don't flash indicator for fast loads (400ms threshold)
});

// 2. Provide route loaders as usual
docInjector.set('customContexts:routeLoader', {
  async loadUser({ params, signal }) {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${params.id}`, { signal });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error('User not found');
    return res.json();
  }
});</code></pre>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!-- 3. Router consumes both: routeLoader for data, loaderIntent for UX --&gt;
&lt;route-view&gt;
  &lt;template route="/users/:id" route:loader="loadUser"&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;{{ '@route.data.name' }}&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;/template&gt;
&lt;/route-view&gt;</code></pre>
<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    When <code>loadUser</code> runs, the router resolves <code>customContexts:loaderIntent</code> from the injector chain.
    The <code>soft</code> strategy activates <code>withSoftBlocking</code>: the previous route content stays visible but
    non-interactive (<code>aria-busy="true"</code>, reduced opacity, <code>pointer-events: none</code>).
    Because <code>timing</code> is <code>debounced</code>, the loading indicator only appears if the loader takes longer than 400ms.
</p>

<h3>Trait-to-Behavior Mapping</h3>
<p>Each trait maps to a specific <a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a> dimension value and applies concrete DOM/ARIA/CSS changes.</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Trait</th>
            <th>Intent Dimension</th>
            <th>DOM Behavior</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withSoftBlocking</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.strategy.soft</code></td>
            <td>Sets <code>aria-busy="true"</code> on the target region. Applies <code>pointer-events: none</code> and reduced opacity. Content remains visible but non-interactive.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withHardBlocking</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.strategy.hard</code></td>
            <td>Injects overlay element over target region. Sets <code>aria-busy="true"</code>. Traps focus within the overlay. User must wait.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withReplacement</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.strategy.replacement</code></td>
            <td>Hides current content via the virtual comment boundary. Stamps loading template (skeleton or spinner) in its place. Swaps back on resolve.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withOptimistic</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.strategy.optimistic</code></td>
            <td>No visual loading state. Previous content stays fully interactive. On success, new content stamps normally. On error, reverts to previous state and surfaces the error.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withDeterminate</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.progress.determinate</code></td>
            <td>Renders native <code>&lt;progress&gt;</code> element with <code>value</code>/<code>max</code> attributes. Updates via the loader's progress callback.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withIndeterminate</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.progress.indeterminate</code></td>
            <td>Renders activity indication (spinner, pulse, or shimmer animation) without measurable progress.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withSkeleton</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.context.initial</code></td>
            <td>Stamps skeleton template matching the expected content structure. Used when no prior content exists (first load).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>withStaleWhileRevalidate</code></td>
            <td><code>loader.context.transition</code></td>
            <td>Keeps previous content visible in a dimmed/stale state while new content loads. Prevents the "spinner replacing content" anti-pattern.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Strategy Comparison</h3>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Strategy</th>
            <th>User Can Interact?</th>
            <th>Content Visible?</th>
            <th>Best For</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>optimistic</code></td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Yes (predicted)</td>
            <td>Fast writes, background sync, real-time collaboration</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>soft</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Yes (dimmed)</td>
            <td>Route transitions, form submissions, data refresh</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>hard</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Obscured</td>
            <td>Payment processing, destructive actions, critical workflows</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>replacement</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>No (placeholder)</td>
            <td>Initial page loads, heavy dashboards, skeleton screens</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Registry-First Philosophy</h3>
<p>
    Loading templates (skeletons, error cards, empty states) are best defined in a global
    <strong>CustomResourceRegistry</strong> rather than inline. This ensures consistent loading
    visuals across the application.
</p>
<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Register reusable loading templates
customResources.define('user-profile', {
    loader: 'skeleton-profile',   // skeleton template name
    error: 'error-card'           // error template name
});</code></pre>

<h3>Virtual Implementation</h3>
<p>
    Uses Custom Comments (e.g. <code>&lt;!-- resource:loader --&gt;</code>) to wrap content.
    This ensures no extra <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> wrappers are introduced, maintaining strict
    parent-child layout relationships (Grid/Flex) while swapping between states.
</p>

<h3>State Machine</h3>
<p>The full lifecycle for a loading operation. Traits react to state transitions and apply the appropriate DOM changes.</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>State</th>
            <th>Description</th>
            <th>Trait Behavior</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>idle</code></td>
            <td>No operation in progress. Default state.</td>
            <td>No loading indicators. Content (if any) rendered normally.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>pending</code></td>
            <td>Operation started, timing threshold not yet reached.</td>
            <td>If <code>timing: 'debounced'</code>, no visible change yet. If <code>timing: 'immediate'</code>, loading indicator activates.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>loading</code></td>
            <td>Timing threshold reached, actively loading.</td>
            <td>Strategy trait activates: soft dims content, hard shows overlay, replacement swaps to skeleton.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>success</code></td>
            <td>Operation completed. Data available.</td>
            <td>Trait cleans up (removes aria-busy, overlay, skeleton). Consumer stamps result content.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>empty</code></td>
            <td>Success but no data.</td>
            <td>Trait cleans up. Consumer renders <code>empty</code> template if registered.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>error</code></td>
            <td>Operation failed.</td>
            <td>Trait cleans up. Consumer renders <code>error</code> template. For optimistic strategy, reverts to previous state.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>stale</code></td>
            <td>Showing previous data while a refresh is in progress.</td>
            <td><code>withStaleWhileRevalidate</code> dims content. Combines with <code>transition</code> context.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Non-Router Consumers</h3>
<p>
    Resource Loader is not router-specific. Any block that performs async work can consume the
    <a href="/intents/loader/">Loader Intent</a> through the same trait system:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Forms</strong> — Submit button uses <code>withSoftBlocking</code> on the form region during submission</li>
    <li><strong>Data grids</strong> — Uses <code>withStaleWhileRevalidate</code> when refreshing table data</li>
    <li><strong>Infinite scroll</strong> — Uses <code>withIndeterminate</code> at the scroll boundary</li>
    <li><strong>File uploads</strong> — Uses <code>withDeterminate</code> to show upload progress</li>
</ul>

<h3>Timing Integration</h3>
<p>
    The <code>timing</code> dimension controls when loading indicators appear. This prevents the
    "flash of loading state" anti-pattern for fast operations.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Timing</th>
            <th>Default Delay</th>
            <th>Behavior</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>immediate</code></td>
            <td>0ms</td>
            <td>Loading indicator appears as soon as the operation starts.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>debounced</code></td>
            <td>400ms</td>
            <td>Loading indicator deferred. If the operation resolves before the threshold, no indicator is ever shown.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>[custom]</code></td>
            <td>User-defined</td>
            <td>Custom timing keys (e.g., <code>slow: 1000</code>) registered in the Loader Intent configuration.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Infrastructure Integration</h3>
<p>
    Resource Loader is the <strong>UI consumption layer</strong> for the <a href="/projects/webresources/">Web Resources</a>
    infrastructure standards. It doesn't own data fetching &mdash; it owns the loading UX.
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Sub-Standard</th><th>Role</th><th>How Resource Loader Uses It</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/clients/">Custom Clients</a></td>
            <td>Transport</td>
            <td>Client executes the <code>ResourceOperation</code>; Resource Loader consumes the result and manages UI state</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/middleware/">Custom Middleware</a></td>
            <td>Interceptors</td>
            <td>Middleware wraps client execution (auth headers, logging, retry). Transparent to Resource Loader.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/cache/">Custom Cache</a></td>
            <td>Cache policy</td>
            <td>Cache policy determines stale-while-revalidate timing. <code>withStaleWhileRevalidate</code> trait activates when cache returns stale data.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/tracer/">Custom Tracer</a></td>
            <td>Observability</td>
            <td>Tracer instruments the operation lifecycle. Injects W3C Trace Context headers. Transparent to Resource Loader.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/pagination/">Custom Pagination</a></td>
            <td>Iteration</td>
            <td>Pagination drives infinite scroll / paginated lists. Resource Loader manages the loading UX for each page fetch.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="/resources/resources/">Custom Resources</a></td>
            <td>Registry</td>
            <td>Registry maps entity names to configs (skeleton templates, error cards, cache strategy). Resource Loader resolves these for consistent loading visuals.</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Events</h3>
<p>
    Resource Loader dispatches typed event classes registered via <a href="/projects/webevents/">Web Events</a> provider keys.
    This enables <code>listenForScoped</code> discrimination when multiple loaders coexist (e.g., router loader + inline data grid loader firing <code>load-end</code> simultaneously).
</p>
<table>
    <thead>
        <tr><th>Event</th><th>Class</th><th>Provider Key</th><th>Detail</th><th>Cancelable</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-load-start</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceLoadStartEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-load-start</code></td>
            <td><code>{ operation, timing }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-load-end</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceLoadEndEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-load-end</code></td>
            <td><code>{ operation, data, duration }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-load-error</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceLoadErrorEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-load-error</code></td>
            <td><code>{ operation, error, retryable }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>resource-state-change</code></td>
            <td><code>ResourceStateChangeEvent</code></td>
            <td><code>customEvents:resource-state-change</code></td>
            <td><code>{ oldState, newState }</code></td>
            <td>No</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Interface</h3>
<pre><code class="language-typescript">/**
 * Loader Intent profile — declares how loading states affect the UI.
 * Provided via customContexts:loaderIntent on the injector chain.
 *
 * Consumers (Router, forms, etc.) resolve this and select
 * matching Resource Loader traits.
 */
interface LoaderIntent {
    strategy: 'optimistic' | 'soft' | 'hard' | 'replacement';
    scope: 'element' | 'region' | 'viewport';
    progress: 'determinate' | 'indeterminate';
    context: 'initial' | 'transition';
    timing: 'immediate' | 'debounced' | string;
    label?: string;
}

/** State machine for loading lifecycle */
type LoaderState = 'idle' | 'pending' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'empty' | 'error' | 'stale';</code></pre>

